<div class="box">
<div class="doc"><p>As good as <b>Mail::Audit</b> is, I wouldn't want to set up
a new rule for every mailing list I'm on.  And this is where
<b>Mail::ListDetector</b> (via the <b>Mail::Audit</b> plugin <b>Mail::Audit::List</b>) comes
in.  <b>Mail::ListDetector</b> automatically can detect if mails were sent to a
mailing list from the headers contained in the mail and as if by magic
move the mail into a appropriately named folder.</p>
<p>A Simple to use, no-brainer of a module that does exactly what it says
on the tin.  And this module my friends, is why I could never move to Outlook.</p>
</div>
<div class="mylink"><a href="http://search.cpan.org/perldoc?Mail::ListDetector">[Read the documentation for Mail::ListDetector on search.cpan.org]</a></div>
</div>



